\f0\i0 \cf4 \cb6 3\'a0of\'a0110\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf4 \cb5 Which of the following statements is TRUE regarding free cash flow to the firm?\cb1 \
\cb5 QID:\'a02840183\cb1 \
\cb5 Mark For Review\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl600\partightenfactor0

\f4\b0\fs60 \cf4 \cb6 A\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl600\partightenfactor0

\fs34 \cf4 \cb6 It represents cash flow before operating expenses have been covered\
\pard\pardeftab720\sl600\partightenfactor0

\f1\b\fs60 \cf11 \'a0\'a0\'a0\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl600\partightenfactor0

\f0\fs34 \cf9 \cb6 It is the amount available to the equity providers of capital only\
\pard\pardeftab720\sl600\partightenfactor0

\f4\b0\fs60 \cf4 C\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl600\partightenfactor0

\fs34 \cf4 \cb6 It represents cash flow before the payment of taxes\
\pard\pardeftab720\sl600\partightenfactor0

\f1\b\fs60 \cf8 \'a0\'a0\'a0\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl600\partightenfactor0

\f4\b0\fs34 \cf4 \cb6 It represents cash flow after operating expenses have been covered\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f0\b\fs47\fsmilli23800 \cf12 \cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl1180\partightenfactor0
\cf9 \cb5 INCORRECT ANSWER CHOSEN\cf12 \cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f7\i\b0\fs34 \cf4 \cb5 Free cash flow to the firm represents cash flow available to the providers of capital, both bondholders and stockholders, after operating expenses have been covered. Operating expenses include working capital (investments in inventory), fixed capital (investment in new equipment), and the payment of taxes.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa272\partightenfactor0

\f8\b \cf4 (30350)\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\qc\partightenfactor0

\f0\i0 \cf4 \cb6 4\'a0of\'a0110\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf4 \cb5 A company switching its inventory accounting method from first-in, first-out (FIFO) to last-in, first-out (LIFO) during an inflationary environment will experience which TWO of the following choices?\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0
\ls2\ilvl0\cf4 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	I.	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
The cost of goods sold will increase\cb1 \
\ls2\ilvl0\cb5 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	II.	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
The cost of goods sold will decrease\cb1 \
\ls2\ilvl0\cb5 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	III.	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
The income tax will increase\cb1 \
\ls2\ilvl0\cb5 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	IV.	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
The income tax will decrease\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf4 \cb5 QID:\'a02840171\cb1 \
\cb5 Mark For Review\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl600\partightenfactor0

\f4\b0\fs60 \cf4 \cb6 A\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl600\partightenfactor0

\fs34 \cf4 \cb6 I and III\
\pard\pardeftab720\sl600\partightenfactor0

\f1\b\fs60 \cf8 \'a0\'a0\'a0\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl600\partightenfactor0

\f0\fs34 \cf9 \cb6 I and IV\
\pard\pardeftab720\sl600\partightenfactor0

\f4\b0\fs60 \cf4 C\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl600\partightenfactor0

\fs34 \cf4 \cb6 II and III\
\pard\pardeftab720\sl600\partightenfactor0

\fs60 \cf4 D\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl600\partightenfactor0

\fs34 \cf4 \cb6 II and IV\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f0\b\fs47\fsmilli23800 \cf10 \cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl1180\partightenfactor0
\cf9 \cb5 CORRECT ANSWER CHOSEN\cf10 \cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f7\i\b0\fs34 \cf4 \cb5 Last-in, first-out accounting would reflect a higher cost of goods sold. The latest inventory would be produced at a higher cost. Since this inventory is used first, it is more expensive than the first-in inventory method during an inflationary period. Changing the inventory method from FIFO to LIFO would increase expenses, not reduce expenses, since we assume a rising price environment. With this inventory method (LIFO), the company would show a lower EBIT and, therefore, lower taxes.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa272\partightenfactor0

\f8\b \cf4 (74336)\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\qc\partightenfactor0

\f0\i0 \cf4 \cb6 5\'a0of\'a0110\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf4 \cb5 In an M&A transaction, which of the following factors is MOST important in determining the long-term value created by a potential acquisition to the acquiring company?\cb1 \
\cb5 QID:\'a02840187\cb1 \
\cb5 Mark For Review\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl600\partightenfactor0

\f1\fs60 \cf11 \cb6 \'a0\'a0\'a0\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl600\partightenfactor0

\f0\fs34 \cf9 \cb6 A positive change in operating margin of the combined companies\
\pard\pardeftab720\sl600\partightenfactor0

\f4\b0\fs60 \cf4 B\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl600\partightenfactor0

\fs34 \cf4 \cb6 Whether the acquisition is accretive to EPS\
\pard\pardeftab720\sl600\partightenfactor0

\fs60 \cf4 C\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl600\partightenfactor0

\fs34 \cf4 \cb6 The growth rate of the combined companies\
\pard\pardeftab720\sl600\partightenfactor0

\f1\b\fs60 \cf8 \'a0\'a0\'a0\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl600\partightenfactor0

\f4\b0\fs34 \cf4 \cb6 Whether the acquisition will increase its return on invested capital\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f0\b\fs47\fsmilli23800 \cf12 \cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl1180\partightenfactor0
\cf9 \cb5 INCORRECT ANSWER CHOSEN\cf12 \cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f7\i\b0\fs34 \cf4 \cb5 This question is asking for the\'a0most\'a0important factor. The acquiring company should look to the return on invested capital, and whether the acquisition will provide returns that cover the cost of invested capital. If this is accomplished, the expectation would be reflected in improvements such as earnings per share and operating margins. The acquisition being accretive to EPS is important in the short term but, in the long term, it is return on invested capital (ROIC).\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa272\partightenfactor0

\f8\b \cf4 (30401)\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\qc\partightenfactor0

\f0\i0 \cf4 \cb6 6\'a0of\'a0110\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf4 \cb5 While preparing an assessment on a company, you have been asked to project the company's earnings. The company had owned an asset with a cost of $120 MM which was sold for $130 MM. In the same period, the company reported net income of $35 MM. The company has a marginal tax rate of 40% and an effective tax rate of 30%. What would be the company's net income without the onetime sale?\cb1 \
\cb5 QID:\'a02840191\cb1 \
\cb5 Mark For Review\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl600\partightenfactor0

\f4\b0\fs60 \cf4 \cb6 A\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl600\partightenfactor0

\fs34 \cf4 \cb6 $28 MM\
\pard\pardeftab720\sl600\partightenfactor0

\f1\b\fs60 \cf8 \'a0\'a0\'a0\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl600\partightenfactor0

\f0\fs34 \cf9 \cb6 $29 MM\
\pard\pardeftab720\sl600\partightenfactor0

\f4\b0\fs60 \cf4 C\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl600\partightenfactor0

\fs34 \cf4 \cb6 $41 MM\
\pard\pardeftab720\sl600\partightenfactor0

\fs60 \cf4 D\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl600\partightenfactor0

\fs34 \cf4 \cb6 $42 MM\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f0\b\fs47\fsmilli23800 \cf10 \cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl1180\partightenfactor0
\cf9 \cb5 CORRECT ANSWER CHOSEN\cf10 \cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f7\i\b0\fs34 \cf4 \cb5 An analyst may be asked to adjust a company's earnings due to a nonrecurring gain or loss such as the sale of a business or asset, a onetime charge, or a restructuring or impairment charge. To calculate the projected income without the nonrecurring gain, subtract the tax-adjusted gain from the net income. The tax-adjusted gain is $6 MM ($10 MM x 60%, the complement of 40%). The net income without the gain would be $29 MM ($35 MM - $6 MM). For this type of calculation, use the marginal tax rate, not the effective tax rate since it is a more conservative number. The marginal tax rate includes both the statutory federal and state taxes, is considered the rate for any additional dollars of income, and does not include many of the adjustments made to calculate a company's effective tax rate (which is a blended rate and is usually lower than the marginal tax rate).\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa272\partightenfactor0

