\f7\i\b0\fs34 \cf4 \cb5 When a company borrows on a short-term basis working capital remains the same, because current assets increase by the same amount as current liabilities. Current ratio will decrease if current assets are greater than current liabilities. Current ratio will increase if current assets are less than current liabilities. In this example, current assets are greater than current liabilities; therefore, current ratio decreases. This is because the increase in the numerator is proportionally less than the increase in the denominator.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa272\partightenfactor0

\f8\b \cf4 \ul Working Capital = Current Assets - Current liabilities\cb1 \ulnone \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa272\partightenfactor0
\cf4 \cb5 Working Capital (Before) = $800,000 - $500,000 = $300,000\cb1 \uc0\u8232 \cb5 Working Capital (After) = $900,000 - $600,000 = $300,000\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa272\partightenfactor0
\cf4 \cb5 \ul Current Ratio = Current Assets / Current Liabilities\cb1 \ulnone \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa272\partightenfactor0
\cf4 \cb5 Current Ratio Before = $800,000 / $500,000 = 1.60\cb1 \uc0\u8232 \cb5 Current Ratio After = $900,000 / $600,000 = 1.50\cb1 \
\cb5 (30137)\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\qc\partightenfactor0

