\f7\i\b0\fs34 \cf4 \cb5 An analyst may be asked to adjust a company's earnings due to a nonrecurring gain or loss such as the sale of a business or asset, a onetime charge, or a restructuring, or impairment charge. To calculate the projected income without the nonrecurring loss, add the tax-adjusted loss to the net income. The tax-adjusted loss is $11.85 MM ($15 MM x 79%, the complement of 21%). The net income without the loss would be $63.85 MM ($52 MM + $11.85 MM). For this type of calculation, use the marginal tax rate, not the effective tax rate. The marginal tax rate is the rate for each additional dollar of income, and does not include many of the adjustments made to calculate a company's effective tax rate (which is a blended rate and is usually lower than the marginal tax rate).\
