\f7\i\b0\fs34 \cf4 \cb5 EV/EBITDA is a popular ratio used among investment bankers. It looks at the value of the entire company as a percentage of its earnings before interest, taxes, depreciation and amortization (EBITDA). It\'92s popular because by using EBITDA, which represents operating earnings without the subtraction of interest expense, depreciation, and amortization, it neutralizes the effect of different capital structures and different accounting methods for depreciation and amortization. Based on historical averages, a particular industry would have a range of EV/EBITDA ratios that would signify an overvalued or undervalued situation. The dividend discount model and the Gordon model are similar to each other, but the Gordon model should be used to value a firm that\'92s in a steady state with dividends growing at a steady rate and expected to stay stable in the long term. EV/EBITDA is often used to compare companies in capital intensive industries.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa272\partightenfactor0

