\f7\i\b0\fs34 \cf4 \cb5 If the risk-free rate increases, while the expected market return remains stable, a company that has a beta less than 1.0 will experience an increase in the weighted average cost of capital (WACC). This would have a negative effect on the valuation of the company. For example, if the expected return of the market was 9% and the risk-free rate was 3%, according to the Capital Asset Pricing Model (CAPM), a company with a beta of .65 would have an equity cost of capital of 6.9%.\
