\f7\i\b0\fs34 \cf4 \cb5 Shares are often priced well above par value in an offering. This excess is recorded on the balance sheet as Capital Surplus. For example, if a company prices an IPO at $18 per share and the par value is $10 per share, then $8 is added to the Capital Surplus in the stockholders' equity section of the balance sheet. A more common term for this excess is Additional Paid-in Capital or Capital in Excess of Par. Retained earnings can also be referred to as earned surplus.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa272\partightenfactor0

