\f8\i\fs34 \cf4 \cb5 Company A's EBIT margin is larger than its EBITDA margin. EBITDA (earnings before interest, taxes, depreciation, and amortization) should be a larger number than EBIT (earnings before interest and taxes). Therefore, when determining its respective margins by dividing by revenue, EBITDA margin should be greater than EBIT margin (EBITDA Margin = EBITDA/Revenue. EBIT Margin = EBIT/Revenue).\cb1 \
