\f8\i\b\fs34 \cf4 \cb5 When using an arithmetic average of the annual growth rates to estimate the CAGR, the estimated CAGR calculated will be higher than the actual CAGR. This is because the true CAGR is calculated using a geometric average. This could present a problem if all the other answer choices are lower than the arithmetic mean average. In the above example, the CAGR estimated using an arithmetic average is -3.4% and all the other answer choices are less than -3.4% (they are more negative). So which one should be chosen? The iteration method can be used to find the correct answer.\cb1 \
\cb5 To use the iteration method, multiply the beginning number in the series by (1 + CAGR) in the answer choice. Multiply the resulting product by (1 + CAGR) again. Complete this process for the number of growth periods in the series. The iteration method can be used to test each answer choice to see which one produces a number closest to the ending number in the series. The answer choice that produces a number closest to the ending number in the series is likely the correct answer choice.\cb1 \
\cb5 In the tables below, it becomes evident that the correct answer is -3.75% when using the iteration method. Calculating the true CAGR by using a geometric average would reveal a CAGR of -3.75%. Because financial calculators are not permitted in the exam room and only four function calculators are made available, the test taker must rely on the iteration method to estimate the CAGR. Although the arithmetic average will get us close, it may be less reliable when there are multiple answer choices each less than the arithmetic mean. Under these circumstances use the iteration method.\cb1 \
\cb5 The correct answer choice should produce a Year 4 ending value closest to 535.\cb1 \
