\cf4 \cb5 The Octane Corporation has invested capital of $2.4 billion, its ROIC is 9%, it has a debt to equity ratio of 100%, a pretax cost of debt of 10%, a marginal tax rate of 40%, and its WACC is 12%. Given that Octane reported $216 million of net income at year end, the estimate of Octane's enterprise value is:\cb1 \
\cb5 QID:\'a02840166\cb1 \
\cb5 Mark For Review\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl600\partightenfactor0

\f1\fs60 \cf11 \cb6 \'a0\'a0\'a0\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl600\partightenfactor0

\f0\fs34 \cf9 \cb6 $2.4 billion\
\pard\pardeftab720\sl600\partightenfactor0

\f4\b0\fs60 \cf4 B\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl600\partightenfactor0

\fs34 \cf4 \cb6 $3.2 billion\
\pard\pardeftab720\sl600\partightenfactor0

\fs60 \cf4 C\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl600\partightenfactor0

\fs34 \cf4 \cb6 $216 million\
\pard\pardeftab720\sl600\partightenfactor0

\f1\b\fs60 \cf8 \'a0\'a0\'a0\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl600\partightenfactor0

\f4\b0\fs34 \cf4 \cb6 $1.8 billion\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f0\b\fs47\fsmilli23800 \cf12 \cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl1180\partightenfactor0
\cf9 \cb5 INCORRECT ANSWER CHOSEN\cf12 \cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f7\i\b0\fs34 \cf4 \cb5 The ROIC to WACC ratio is ROIC divided by WACC. A ratio of greater than 1.0 is an indication that the company is creating value. A ratio of less than 1.0 is an indication that the company is destroying value. The ROIC to WACC ratio can be used to estimate the enterprise value (EV) of a company. The model assumes that the ratio of enterprise value to invested capital (IC) is equal to the ratio of ROIC to WACC.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa272\partightenfactor0

\f8\b \cf4 (EV \'f7 IC) = (ROIC \'f7 WACC)\cb1 \
\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f11\fs40\fsmilli20400 \cf4 \cb5       Alternatively 
\f12\b0\fs34 \cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa272\partightenfactor0

\f8\b \cf4 \cb5 EV = IC x (ROIC \'f7 WACC)\cb1 \
\cb5 EV = $2.4 billion x (9% \'f7 12%)\cb1 \
\cb5 EV = $2.4 billion x 75%\cb1 \
\cb5 EV = $1.8 billion\cb1 \
\cb5 With $2.4 billion of invested capital and a ROIC to WACC ratio of 75%, Octane's enterprise value is estimated to be $1.8 billion. Notice that Octane's estimated enterprise value is less than the book value of its invested capital of $2.4 billion. This is because the ROIC - WACC spread is negative (9% - 12% = - 3%). The company is destroying 3 cents of value for every dollar invested. Although the company is generating an accounting profit, it is not earning its cost of capital. For example, its revenue may be exceeding its expenses, but its returns are not exceeding the cost of capital. In other words, providers of capital are getting a return on their investment that is less than they expected.\cb1 \
\cb5 (30596)\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\qc\partightenfactor0

