\fs47\fsmilli23800 \cf10 \cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl1180\partightenfactor0
\cf9 \cb5 CORRECT ANSWER CHOSEN\cf10 \cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f7\i\b0\fs34 \cf4 \cb5 If a company announces that it will acquire a foreign company, and at the time of the closing of the acquisition the target company's currency has declined in value, the cost of the acquisition will have declined. For example, if the euro was currently trading at 1.24 and the Italian company announced a purchase of the U.S. company for $21,000,000, this equals 16,935,483 euros ($21,000,000 / 1.24). At the time of the closing, if the euro was trading at 1.35, the U.S. dollar has weakened and the cost of the acquisition to the Italian company is now 15,555,555 euros ($21,000,000 / 1.35). The Italian company's price would have declined by 1,379,928 euros. There is nothing to suggest that the Italian company will purchase other U.S. companies after it has acquired the U.S. sunglasses company.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa272\partightenfactor0

