\cf9 \cb5 CORRECT ANSWER CHOSEN\cf10 \cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f7\i\b0\fs34 \cf4 \cb5 The core profitability of a company can be skewed by non-recurring items. Non-recurring items are items that are assumed to be infrequent or unusual such as severance packages, litigation charges, reorganization costs, impairments, repairs from storm damage, and the sale of an asset at a gain or loss. Because these items are non-operating in nature and reported pretax, an analyst may make adjustments for these items by adding back to income from continuing operations tax adjusted, non-recurring losses, or subtracting from income from continuing operations tax adjusted, non-recurring gains. This will provide a better perspective of what the company could have earned if these events had not occurred.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa272\partightenfactor0

\f8\b \cf4 Do not confuse non-recurring items, which are pretax items, with gains and losses from discontinued operations. Discontinued operations are reported when an entire group of assets, like an entire business division is sold. Because activities from these operations have been discontinued, revenue and expense associated with them are stripped out of continuing revenue and expense and reported separately on an after-tax basis under a line item called discontinued operations. Gains and losses from discontinued operations are ignored when determining the core profitability of a company.\cb1 \
\cb5 Also, do not confuse non-recurring items with extraordinary items. Extraordinary items are no longer permitted under GAAP as of January 2018. Extraordinary items were once reported on an after-tax basis similar to discontinued operations. In order for an item to be considered extraordinary it had to be both infrequent and unusual. Because of the difficulty in determining what is both infrequent and unusual, the use of extraordinary items has been discontinued.\cb1 \
\cb5 (17121)\cb1 \
