\f7\i\b0\fs34 \cf4 \cb5 Original revenue: 800,000 units x $1.50 price = $1,200,000\cb1 \
\cb5 Revenue after 10% increase in demand and 10% decline in price:\cb1 \
\cb5 880,000 new units sold x $1.35 new price = $1,188,000 new revenue\cb1 \
\cb5 Revenue has declined by $12,000 ($1,188,000 new revenue - $1,200,000 original revenue). $12,000 decline in revenue / $1,200,000 original revenue = 1% decline in revenue\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa272\partightenfactor0

\f8\b \cf4 Original total costs: $300,000 fixed costs + $340,000 variable costs = $640,000 total original costs\cb1 \uc0\u8232 \cb5 The fixed costs will not be impacted by a 10% increase in demand; however, total variable costs will rise if the firm produces 10% more to meet the demand. The original variable cost per unit: $340,000 original variable costs / 800,000 units = $.425 per unit;\cb1 \uc0\u8232 \cb5 New variable costs: 880,000 new units x $.425 variable cost per unit = $374,000 new variable costs\cb1 \uc0\u8232 \cb5 New total costs: $300,000 fixed + $374,000 new variable costs = $674,000 new total costs\cb1 \
\cb5 Original gross profit: $1,200,000 original revenue - $640,000 original total costs = $560,000 original gross income\cb1 \uc0\u8232 \cb5 Original gross margin: $560,000 gross income / $1,200,000 original revenue = .467, or 46.7%\cb1 \
\cb5 Gross profit after changes: $1,188,000 new revenue - $674,000 new total costs = $514,000 new gross income\cb1 \uc0\u8232 \cb5 New gross margin: $514,000 new gross income / $1,188,000 new revenue = .433, or 43.3%\cb1 \
\cb5 (18624)\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\qc\partightenfactor0

