\f7\i\b0\fs34 \cf4 \cb5 The net income reported by Company Q is $48 million, based on a net profit margin of 8% and revenue of $600 million. Working backwards from the net profit, pretax income is $73.85 MM [$48 MM / (1.0-35%)]. The EBIT is $123.85 MM ($73.85 MM + $50 MM). Next we will assess the changes to the company's financials.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa272\partightenfactor0

\f8\b \cf4 If the tax rate falls from 35% to 32%, the net income would be $73.85 MM multiplied by the complement of the new tax rate of .68, which equals $50.22 MM. This would represent a $2.22 MM increase in net income.\cb1 \
\cb5 If interest expense fell to $46 MM, the reduction of $4 MM, would produce a net income increase of $2.6 MM ($4 MM multiplied by the complement of the tax rate of .65, equals $2.6 MM). This event would have the most significant impact on net income.\cb1 \
\cb5 If depreciation fell by $1 million, the net income would rise by $650,000 ($1,000,000 x .65 = $650,000).\cb1 \
\cb5 If the net profit margin increased by 25 basis points to 8.25%, the net income would rise to $49.5 MM (.0825 x $600 MM = $49.5 MM), an increase of 1.5 MM.\cb1 \
