\f4\b0\fs60 \cf4 \cb6 A\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl600\partightenfactor0

\fs34 \cf4 \cb6 FCFF is used to evaluate leveraged companies while FCFE is used to evaluate companies without debt\
\pard\pardeftab720\sl600\partightenfactor0

\f1\b\fs60 \cf8 \'a0\'a0\'a0\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl600\partightenfactor0

\f0\fs34 \cf9 \cb6 There is no difference in an unleveraged company\
\pard\pardeftab720\sl600\partightenfactor0

\f4\b0\fs60 \cf4 C\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl600\partightenfactor0

\fs34 \cf4 \cb6 FCFF is used for companies with low capital expenditures while FCFE is used for companies with high depreciation\
\pard\pardeftab720\sl600\partightenfactor0

\fs60 \cf4 D\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl600\partightenfactor0

\fs34 \cf4 \cb6 Only FCFE is adjusted for depreciation, capital expenditures, and changes to working capital accounts\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f0\b\fs47\fsmilli23800 \cf10 \cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl1180\partightenfactor0
\cf9 \cb5 CORRECT ANSWER CHOSEN\cf10 \cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f7\i\b0\fs34 \cf4 \cb5 Free cash flow for the firm (FCFF) is used to evaluate the profitability of an entire business, rather than shareholder equity. The starting point for FCFF is EBIT multiplied by (1 - tax rate) and then adding depreciation and amortization, subtracting capital expenditures, and factoring in changes to working capital (WC). Increases in WC reduce FCFF; decreases in WC increase FCFF. It is also useful when evaluating companies with little or no debt. FCFE describes the funds available to owners of a company. Rather than beginning with EBIT, FCFE begins with net income. The adjustments made for depreciation and amortization, capital expenditures and working capital are the same as described for FCFF. Therefore, if a firm has no debt, FCFF and FCFE are the same.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa272\partightenfactor0

\f8\b \cf4 (30344)\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\qc\partightenfactor0

\f0\i0 \cf4 \cb6 101\'a0of\'a0110\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf4 \cb5 The MackLear Corporation has invested capital of $4 billion, its ROIC is 18%, it has a debt to equity ratio of 100%, a pretax cost of debt of 10%, a marginal tax rate of 40%, its WACC is 12%, $200 million of cash and 60 million shares outstanding. An estimate of MackLear's price per share is:\cb1 \
\cb5 QID:\'a02840242\cb1 \
\cb5 Mark For Review\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl600\partightenfactor0

\f4\b0\fs60 \cf4 \cb6 A\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl600\partightenfactor0

\fs34 \cf4 \cb6 $100\
\pard\pardeftab720\sl600\partightenfactor0

\f1\b\fs60 \cf8 \'a0\'a0\'a0\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl600\partightenfactor0

\f0\fs34 \cf9 \cb6 $70\
\pard\pardeftab720\sl600\partightenfactor0

\f4\b0\fs60 \cf4 C\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl600\partightenfactor0

\fs34 \cf4 \cb6 $67\
\pard\pardeftab720\sl600\partightenfactor0

\fs60 \cf4 D\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl600\partightenfactor0

\fs34 \cf4 \cb6 $14.66\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f0\b\fs47\fsmilli23800 \cf10 \cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl1180\partightenfactor0
\cf9 \cb5 CORRECT ANSWER CHOSEN\cf10 \cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f7\i\b0\fs34 \cf4 \cb5 The ROIC to WACC ratio is ROIC divided by WACC. A ratio of greater than 1.0 is an indication that the company is creating value. A ratio of less than 1.0 is an indication that the company is destroying value. The ROIC to WACC ratio can be used to estimate the enterprise value (EV) of a company, which is also required to estimate MackLear's price per share. The model assumes that the ratio of enterprise value to invested capital (IC) is equal to the ratio of ROIC to WACC.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa272\partightenfactor0

\f8\b \cf4 (EV \'f7 IC) = (ROIC \'f7 WACC)\cb1 \
\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f11\fs40\fsmilli20400 \cf4 \cb5       Alternatively 
\f12\b0\fs34 \cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa272\partightenfactor0

\f8\b \cf4 \cb5 EV = IC x (ROIC \'f7 WACC)\cb1 \
\cb5 EV = $4 billion x (18% \'f7 12%)\cb1 \
\cb5 EV = $4 billion x 150%\cb1 \
\cb5 EV = $6 billion\cb1 \
\cb5 With $4 billion of invested capital and a ROIC to WACC ratio of 150%, MackLear's enterprise value is estimated to be $6 billion. Notice that MackLear's estimated enterprise value is greater than the value of its invested capital of $4 billion. This is because the ROIC - WACC spread is positive. 18% - 12% = 6%. The company is adding 6 cents of value for every dollar invested. The company is earning a return that is greater than its cost of capital. In other words, providers of capital are getting a return on their investment that is greater than they expected.\cb1 \
\cb5 Equity value can be calculated from enterprise value by subtracting debt and adding cash. Because MackLear has invested capital of $4 billion and a debt to equity ratio of 100%, the debt is 50% of total capital. For example, if debt is 100% of equity, then there must be 100 units of debt for every 100 units of equity; therefore, total capital would be debt + equity or 100 units of debt + 100 units of equity, which equals 200 units of total capital. 100 units of debt as a percentage of 200 units of total capital, equals 50% of total capital (100 / 200). Given that MackLear has $4 billion of total capital, 50% of total capital equals $2 billion of debt. The estimated enterprise value of $6.0 billion, less the $2.0 billion of debt, plus the $200 million of cash results in an equity value of $4.2 billion. With 60 million shares outstanding the equity should be valued at $70 per share ($4.2 billion / 60 million shares = $70 per share.\cb1 \
\cb5 (30595)\cb1 \
